Currently, our Terraform registry setup creates a significant headache in our development process. This restriction forces developers to change the source of reusable modules to the prod Terraform registry when preparing for production deployment, while changing back to GitLab during dev cycles.

This setup leads to a cumbersome development cycle:

- Pull the main branch.
- Change all module sources to GitLab paths for development.
- Conduct testing loops until the code is ready for production.
- Change all module sources back to the prod Terraform registry for production deployment.
- Merge changes and deploy to production.

This process is problematic because it involves manual, untested changes in the production environment and absurd tedium and process.

Proposed Solution:

The core of the proposed solution is to leverage GitLab tagging for modules, which already serves as a controlled behavior for ensuring module admission for production. By using the GitLab reference with appropriate tags, we satisfy the same security concerns addressed by using the prod registry. This approach would eliminate the need to change module sources between environments, streamlining the development process, and keeping to the same security controls. Sentinel policies can be authrored to ensure a valid tag in gitlab sources but until then, manual reviews can identify the same concept.

Recommendations:

Admit Limitations: Acknowledge that the current configuration of the prod Terraform registry is inadequate for our needs.
Leverage GitLab Tagging: Utilize GitLab tagging to manage module versions and security, allowing for consistent sourcing across environments.
Fix Terraform Registry Setup: We should amend the Terraform registry configuration to maintain a consistent name in both preprod and prod environments. This consistency will allow for uniform module sourcing across stages. To achieve this, we will implement a controlled pipeline that safeguards the contract of modules and their versions, ensuring they remain identical across both registries.
